@tcNickolas . I finished updating and checking now. You can see the change here.

https://github.com/dongjoon-hyun/reef/blob/3ee72a57cbf5034355ae853a73036293dd3be3ec/lang/java/reef-tang/README.md

`README.md` is slightly updated, too. Please look at that too. If that is not proper, please let me know.

Thank you, @markusweimer and @tcNickolas . Sorry for late response.

@tcNickolas , we should think in terms of the dependencies among REEF layers, too. As you know, `Tang` and `Wake` are conceptually very solid and well designed lower layers of `REEF`. Although the use of `REEFVersion` is just limited in test suites, that will make another dependency in `Tang` module. Actually, `org.apache.reef.util.REEFVersion` is in `reef-common` and `reef-common` has `Tang` dependency up to now.

I prefer to keep the current architectural module design and dependency. How do you think about that?

@afchung Thanks for the detailed explanation and info about how MR does. I totally agree with your idea to provide a way for users to handle the failed operations. And I think the current approach in this PR, seems best between the others described above.

For my second question, I'm sorry that I did not elaborate enough.

I was wondering the case of single function, not aggregation. When a single Taklet has failed, users can't know what was the input/function, but are notified by `onFailure(Throwable)` in [VortexFuture](https://github.com/apache/reef/blob/master/lang/java/reef-applications/reef-vortex/src/main/java/org/apache/reef/vortex/api/VortexFuture.java) (Please correct me if I missed something). So my question was, if we want to provide such information about the failed aggregation, wouldn't it be natural to have the same logic for the single function?
